reviewText: To be ho0nest, I wasn't sure what I was expecting.  Maybe some short films on first love or something along those lines. What I got was not that at all. The cover states contains strong language, sex and violence. It didn't mention terrible stories, terrible acting and just an overall WTF! The stories were pointless other than to show naked or near naked people and forgive me, but I like a good story...it wasn't to be found here. I have said it before, low budget doesn't have to mean bad movie....but here it means dismally horrible.
Skinny shaved bald twinks flitting around in shallow silly stories. I guess if you like that sort of thing go for it, but it's too much like pedophilia with no plot for me.

This is a film like none other that I had seen before. The four separate but connected stories flow seamlessly from one to another and are full of twists and turns along with a cast that rarely is seen wearing much clothing, if any. The writer, director, Steven Vasquez is well known for his stunning cinematography and working with a low budget. This is a must see for fans of Vasquez and his young cast of characters.

If full frontal nudity, soft core porn, and erections are what you seek, then eroddity (which I'm imagining is a combination of "erotic" plus "odd") will get you off. If between your nudity and erections you want a semblance of a story and some decent acting, well, then, you probably want to find "Debbie Does Dallas" or something akin to it.

"Errodity" attempts to play like a series of episodes from the Twilight Zone - at times cheeky, always mysterious, with a sprinkle of life lesson for good measure. Unfortunately, the movie comes across as self-indulgent; a movie made because they could, casting themselves because they could, and referring to themselves as "sexy" ... because they could. And while they were in the midst of congratulating themselves on a job well done, they utterly failed to deliver a humorous line, create an effecting scene, or surprise the audience. Far more odd than erotic, the movie misses as an attempt to deliver a spoof of the Twilight Series or a genuine titillating recreation of it.
